The 2.0.6 release introduced the Parent Link custom field, which exposes the Portfolio hierarchy information in JIRA. This field cannot yet be searched via JQL though.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1577].
  {panel}

Not all projects have the same skills/stages % ratio. Some projects require more design, development etc. It would be useful to define a different mix of skills/stages % for individual issue sources for distributing estimates and calculating the schedule.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1575].
  {panel}

For tighter control of my release scope and date, and not have things added.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1573].
  {panel}

I use Portfolio more for seeing an elegant hierarchy view on a single screen for the status of a particular release, because no other view in JIRA is as useful for doing this (from what I've found in my many years of living Atlassian). A very small amount of time do I use Portfolio to actually do forecasting.

What prevents this from working well for me is that Portfolio will not inherit the assignee from the issue in the view until an estimate value is set for each item.

Can there be an option to inherit the assignee of the issue and show it without requiring an estimate?

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1570].
  {panel}

This new Portfolio JIRA version doesn't support 'Stream' used ad grouping the releases.

It can be resolved by grouping or dividing Projects, but it force us to re-organize legacy projects.

Using traditional version of Portfolio JIRA is not that good choice, because sync doesn't work.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This bug report is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding bug report|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1569].
  {panel}

If there is a Scrum team with more than about 50 persons who have similar skills (or there are no skills defined ad all) and there is a sprint defined where at least one of the resources in the team is overbooked the schedule calculation does not yield any result.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1567].
  {panel}

In the issues I can not read nothing about them.
If I have something like a zoom, or put a date range in order to view less information, but with more details

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1559].
  {panel}

Right now when I create a subtask, it will default to the last project's subtask/story created even if its from another project. Since the project cant be changed once the issue is planned/created the only solution it is to exclude it from the Plan before committing. Further into the problem is that I cant exclude one single subtask; it will exclude the whole Story even if it was committed.

Portfolio needs to auto detect the parent issue's project value and assign it automatically to the newly created subtask.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1558].
  {panel}

It can be easy to miss scheduling errors/warnings if the parent issue is collapsed. It would be good if the parent issues also had an icon next to them (perhaps slightly transparent) if one of their children has an error.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1557].
  {panel}

Hi,

Currently, there are some columns in the timeline view of the scope tab that are not sortable.  It would be very useful to be able to sort the column that shows the warnings.  This way I can group all the warnings together and address them one by one instead of having to scroll and find each warnings among all records.  Screenshot attached.

Great improvements btw in Live Plans, we love it.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1555].
  {panel}

h3. Problem Definition
Let's say, I have one issue PJA-1 - type Task that belongs to ProjectA and linked (relates to, clones, block, etc.) to multiple issues. This issue PJA-1 has been imported to Portfolio and the issue/issues that linked to it should show on issue details view in Portfolio. The actual result is not showing the issue/issues linked to PJA-1.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1552].
  {panel}

Sprints start date currently always start on "today". There should be a configuration that allow this to be customised per team.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1549].
  {panel}

I would be great if there was a way in Portfolio to configure the start of the next sprint to be a set time after the end of the previous sprint. This is to allow time to conduct a retrospective and sprint planning prior to the commencement of the next sprint. Alternatively if we were able to set the sprint length to weeks and days so that you could have a 2 week sprint set for 2 weeks and 2 days and use the current non-working days to reduce the teams capacity to the 2 weeks.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1547].
  {panel}

In order to enable the proposed portfolio structure of JIra Projects = teams/deploy-able assets and Initiative = projects and take advantage of other Add-Ons like story mapping JQL for Initiative and Theme needs to be enabled.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1539].
  {panel}

As part of 2.0.3, when you open an issue detailed view from Scope, you can set its parent issue. However, it would be nice to set the parent via a column in Scope view for easier access.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1530].
  {panel}

I'd like to be able to filter for both "open and completed issues" as well as "date range". Right now the "Scheduled range" will cause all completed issues to also disappear from scope/schedule.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1521].
  {panel}

I want to plan a single stream to be completed by a team so each work item starts after the completion of the previous work item, following rank order. 

h2. Workaround
Using dependencies however for a large scale plan this isn't practical as it requires setting up dependencies for every item in the plan which is very time consuming.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1520].
  {panel}

Using story points, it appears that this chart doesn't discriminate between "Done" issues and those marked as "Duplicate" or "Won't Do".

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1518].
  {panel}

I'm not sure if this is expected behaviour or not, but it is causing some confusion for our users:

If a story is closed in the current sprint, it no longer shows in the schedule, and is removed from the capacity calculations. It's still visible in the scope section. This is problematic for us, as it then appears that there is available capacity in the sprint, when that's not the case. 

To address this, issues that are resolved in a sprint should continue to be visible in the schedule and they should continue to count towards the capacity utilisation for the sprint.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1517].
  {panel}

As a project manager, I need to filter the Epics displayed on the reports so that I can customize roadmaps for specific audiences.  

Some of the Epics that are more operational in nature do not need to be displayed on the Roadmap when it goes to the product owners, who are only interested in seeing which features will be included in the release.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1516].
  {panel}

As a Project Manager, I want to see which Sprints are overallocated if we were to do all of the Stories in a fixed time frame, rather than having Portfolio load balance the work out into future sprints that are beyond our  project timeline.  This would give us reports to use to justify the number of team members we would have to hire to achieve the work load in the specified time period.

Currently the only way to do this is to set fixed Sprint assignments on each story, which then negates the dynamic what if modeling capabilities of Portfolio.

It would be good to be able to set a fixed end date for all of the backlog, and have Porfolio show the over allocations in the Sprints, by Team.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1512].
  {panel}

In our workflow we create sub-tasks 'types' that line up to skills, eg Software Design/Development/Test. When importing a board of the parent issues it becomes a large manual task to sync the sub-tasks types to the related skill column (eg 20+ issues with 4 sub-tasks each = 80 changes).

Having a configuration point in the portfolio store a default mapping to 'type to skill' will quickly solve this and allow the plan to accurately track the projected finish dates. This mapping should also apply upon creation of new sub tasks in the portfolio view, etc.

At the moment the portfolio can't be used by a large number of our teams due to this usability issue.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1508].
  {panel}

Allow users to select items in a Portfolio (Scope) based on a sprint in the same way as I can filter Teams & Releases.

i.e. Filter items for Sprint 27, so that I can check capacity for team members with specialisations for the sprint.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1503].
  {panel}

This would look pretty similar to the hierarchical view on the “Scope” tab of Portfolio. In addition, I should be able to automatically select all children of an issue by selecting the parent (i.e., I select an epic to commit and all its child issues are automatically checked to be committed as well).

This would make it easier to review and commit changes for entire epics or custom issue types (like initiatives)

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1501].
  {panel}

For unestimated issues, it could be useful to have an option that assigns them by default to a team with the corresponding issue source.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1500].
  {panel}

Currently, a user can be a Portfolio Administrator but not have access to the Shared Team Management page. To gain access, they must also have the Shared Team Management permission.

Perhaps the Portfolio Administrator permission should also allow access to Shared Team Management.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1496].
  {panel}

To be able to publish a link to a report that is configured exactly the way I want it.
I want to be able to share this report to stakeholders who wouldn't need to know anything about how Portfolio works.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1494].
  {panel}

When in Manage Shared Teams, I would like to be able to sort the Teams by name as it currently lists them in order of creation date.  This is cumbersome since we have several teams.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1488].
  {panel}

The default value for the _Completion date_ filter is "Completed since beginning of current sprint", even when the plan contains no sprints (e.g. has only Kanban teams). This leads to counterintuitive behaviour, as people may not realise why completed issues are not being shown.

Either the _Completion date_ filter should default to another value (e.g. "This month"), or the UI should otherwise make it clear why completed issues are not showing.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This bug report is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding bug report|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1486].
  {panel}

When I update the velocity of my teams, the future sprints reflect the changes, but the current sprint is incorrect. How do I correct capacity for the current sprint?

!image-2016-06-22-15-58-48-300.png|thumbnail!

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This bug report is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding bug report|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1485].
  {panel}

I defined four teams whose source is a single board. Each team is set up for two week sprints. When I try to remove the grouping on the schedule view, I get the attached error. Unchecking "Sprints" brings the issues back, which still seem to be grouped by sprint -- only the sprint name is omitted. Why does it think that my teams aren't on the same schedule?

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
